  "example_section_data": {
    "children": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "Let's define 3 categories and for a given sample, the sum of the trials\nof each category is 8. The number of trials per category is determined\nby the `pvals` associated to each category.\nThen, we sample this distribution 64 times."
      },
      {
        "type": "code",
        "value": "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nfrom scipy.stats import qmc\ndist = qmc.MultinomialQMC(\n    pvals=[0.2, 0.4, 0.4], n_trials=10, engine=qmc.Halton(d=1)\n)\nsample = dist.random(64)"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "We can plot the sample and verify that the median of number of trials\nfor each category is following the `pvals`. That would be\n``pvals * n_trials = [2, 4, 4]``."
      },
      {
        "type": "code",
        "value": "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\nax.yaxis.get_major_locator().set_params(integer=True)\n_ = ax.boxplot(sample)\nax.set(xlabel=\"Categories\", ylabel=\"Trials\")\nplt.show()"
      },
      {
